observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

Municipal Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count of PPE, including the roads and other road network components, in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, and prepare the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network System using the format provided under Annex “C” of COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Municipal Engineer prepare the Report on Local Road Network using the format provided under Annex “A” of COA Circular No. 2015-008 and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer, copy furnished the Audit Team;

Acting Municipal Treasurer, as the Property Officer, prepare and maintain the Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components, using the format provided under Annex “E” of COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Municipal Accountant (i) prepare a reconciliation of the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network System submitted by the Inventory Committee and the Report on Local Road Network submitted by the Municipal Engineer; (ii) prepare the journal entry to record the beginning balance of the local road network and its components in the general ledger and the Local Road Network Ledger Card, respectively; and (iii) henceforth, ensure adequate disclosure of information regarding the Local Road Network on the Notes to the Financial Statements as prescribed under Annex “B” of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and

Municipal Mayor (i) cause the creation of a plantilla position for the General Services Officer, subject to availability of funds; (ii) through the Human Resource Management Officer, initiate the search for qualified applicants for the said position; and (iii) enjoin the concerned department heads to comply with all the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the:

Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO) - Designate henceforth, impose timely and complete registration of newly hired employees and elected officials to PhilHealth in accordance with Section 15 of the IRR of RA No. 10606;

Municipal Accountant prepare an analysis of unremitted PhilHealth premium contributions, reconcile billings and remittances, and effect necessary adjustment and corrections, as appropriate;

Acting Municipal Treasurer, henceforth, ensure prompt remittance of PhilHealth contributions within the period prescribed by PhilHealth to avoid incurrence of unnecessary interest and penalties; and

Municipal Mayor determine the local officials and/or employees who were responsible for the unnecessary delays in the remittance of PhilHealth premium contributions and cause the refund of interest and surcharges totaling ₱3,015.80.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the Furniture and Fixtures and the Advances to Special Disbursing Officer account balances;

issue demand letters to all accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2019 except those who have already rendered full settlement thereof in CY 2020;

cause the withholding of salaries of accountable officers who still failed to render full settlement of cash advances despite the issuance of demand letter pursuant to Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002; and
henceforth, (i) refrain from processing any additional cash advance to accountable officers who have not yet fully settled their previous cash advance; and (ii) strictly impose the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in order to ensure that all cash advances are liquidated at the end of the year.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant (i) submit a reasonable explanation for failure to detect the deficiencies and errors in the supporting documents for the purchase of drugs and medicines totaling ₱509,753.00; (ii) henceforth, ensure that all supporting documents are thoroughly reviewed as to correctness and completeness before preparation of the DV pursuant to Section 474.b(5) of RA No. 7160; and (iii) exercise prudence in recording financial transactions to ensure correctness of account balances;

BAC Chairman (i) submit a copy of the approved procurement plan, abstracts of price quotations and BAC resolutions pertaining to the purchase of drugs and medicines in CY 2019 totaling ₱509,753.00; and (ii) observe strictly the rules and regulations on procurement prescribed under RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR;

Municipal Health Officer submit a certification that all the drugs and medicines procured in CY 2019 fall within and conform with the current edition of the PNF; otherwise, submit a detailed list of those that did not conform, as the case may be; and

Municipal Mayor install, implement and monitor a sound system of internal control by imposing strict adherence to the instructions on the use of transaction forms prescribed under the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II, with emphasis on the implementation of control numbers and issuance dates.

We recommended that the:

Municipal GFPS Executive Committee and TWG (i) submit to the Audit Team a reasonable explanation for failure to consider the unappropriated amount of ₱98,780.28 during preparation of GPB for CY 2019; (ii) submit the GPB to the DILG within the prescribed period; (iii) henceforth, exert more efforts in identifying GAD strategies and formulating plans based on the results of gender analysis and gender assessment to ensure that at least 5% of the Municipality’s annual budget is appropriated for specific GAD programs, projects and activities; and (iv) strictly observe timely submission of the GPB to the DILG Palawan Provincial Office on or before March 31 of each year;

Local Chief Executive ensure the optimal utilization of GAD budget to address the gender-related issues and concerns within the Municipality.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor the following:

2.1 Instruct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to regularly reconcile their respective books to accounts. Any discrepancy noted should be investigated in accordance with existing regulations and take appropriate action thereon;

The Former ICO-Municipal Treasurer to immediately turn-over all the cash collections in his custody to the new ICO-Municipal Treasurer for deposit to the authorized government depository bank intact, in compliance with Section 32 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I. Likewise, the Former ICO-Municipal Treasurer should submit an explanation letter for not depositing his collections intact and promptly;

The ICO-Municipal Treasurer to comply with Section 59 of NGAS Manual on the procedures for the stale checks. Accordingly, the Municipal Accountant should make the necessary adjustments in the books to account for the stale checks, provided they are supported with the original disbursement vouchers and other supporting documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should submit the AAPSI to the
COA Audit Team timely, completely and accurately. The said AAPSI must indicate
thereto the following:
a. Reference Number;
b. Audit Observations;
c. Audit Recommendations;
d. Agency Action Plan (Action Plan, Person Responsible and Target
Implementation Date);
e. Status of Implementation;
f. Reason for Partial/ Delay/ Non-Implementation, if applicable; and
g. Action Taken/ Action to be taken.

We reiterated our recommendation that the management:

a. Create an inventory team and require them to conduct an immediate physical count of all its PPE to determine the actual existence and proper valuation of the same, pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1. This committee may be composed of the heads or representatives from the Office of the Municipal Treasurer, the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Engineer, and a representative from the Office of the Municipal Mayor;

b. Ensure that physical inventory be undertaken annually and reports be submitted accordingly. Failure to do is an indicative of management’s lack of appreciation on the importance of conducting physical inventory;

c. Require the ICO-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to create, update and maintain the required property cards and ledger cards for PPE, real property and CIP stating the nature, date of acquisition, cost and circumstances of the individual property;

d. Cause the reconciliation of results of the actual count with the property and accounting records. All discrepancies between physical and book inventories must be investigated, adjusted and reconciled immediately; and

e. Submit the RPCPPE to the COA Auditor concerned on or before January 31 of each year.

We reiterated our recommendation that:

a. The Municipal Mayor should enjoin officials and employees concerned to strictly adhere with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, as provided for under COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997. She should likewise designate a disbursing officer who will exclusively handle cash payments of municipal obligations;

b. The Municipal Accountant should closely monitor unsettled cash advances of each officer/employee and send within ten (10) days before the expiration of the prescribed period, a written reminder under the signature of the head of agency or his duly authorized representative, enjoining officials or employees concerned to immediately liquidate their cash advances. Before the approval of the grant of cash advance, she should likewise issue a certification that the previous balances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books and ensure that it is supported with the required documents such as listing/estimate of expenditures, approved payroll, etc.;

c. The Municipal Accountant, ICO-Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Mayor must refrain from processing cash advance vouchers of officials and employees who still have unliquidated balances; and

d. The ICO-Municipal Treasurer should immediately liquidate all his withdrawals granted in 2015 and thereafter.
